            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How the Italian pension system works (in simple terms)</h2>
              <p>
                Italy’s public pension system is managed mainly by
                <strong
                  >INPS (Istituto Nazionale della Previdenza Sociale)</strong
                >. For most workers today, the benefit is calculated with a
                <strong>contribution-based (contributivo)</strong> formula:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Each year, a percentage of your gross salary is paid as
                  <strong>social security contributions</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Those contributions are credited to a
                  <strong>notional account</strong> in your name.
                </li>
                <li>
                  The account is <strong>revalued every year</strong> based on
                  GDP growth (not actual investment returns).
                </li>
                <li>
                  At retirement, the total notional capital is multiplied by an
                  <strong>age-based transformation coefficient</strong> to get
                  your annual pension.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">
                  Simplified formula used by this calculator
                </p>
                <p>Let:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\( S \) = average gross annual salary in Italy</li>
                  <li>\( c \) = total contribution rate (e.g. 0.33 for 33%)</li>
                  <li>\( n \) = years of contributions in Italy</li>
                  <li>
                    \( r \) = annual revaluation rate of the notional account
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    \( k(a) \) = transformation coefficient at retirement age \(
                    a \)
                  </li>
                </ul>
                <p>Then the notional capital is approximated as:</p>
                <p>
                  \( \text{Capital} \approx S \cdot c \cdot \dfrac{(1 + r)^n -
                  1}{r} \)
                </p>
                <p>and the annual pension:</p>
                <p>
                  \( \text{Pensione annua} \approx \text{Capital} \cdot k(a) \)
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Age-based transformation coefficients (approximate)</h3>
              <p>
                The real coefficients are set by law and updated periodically.
                This tool uses a smoothed approximation inspired by recent INPS
                tables:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Age 60: around <strong>4.2%</strong> of capital per year
                </li>
                <li>Age 63: around <strong>4.6%</strong></li>
                <li>Age 67: around <strong>5.2%</strong></li>
                <li>Age 70: around <strong>5.7%</strong></li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The later you retire, the <strong>higher</strong> the
                coefficient and the annual pension, because the same capital is
                spread over fewer expected years of payment.
              </p>

              <h2>Eligibility: minimum age and contribution years</h2>
              <p>
                The calculator performs a
                <strong>basic eligibility check</strong> based on typical rules
                for the Italian system. Exact requirements depend on your
                employment category and the law in force at retirement, but as a
                rough guide:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Standard old-age pension</strong>: at least ~20 years
                  of contributions and an age around 67.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Early retirement</strong>: higher contribution years
                  (for example 41–43 years) and a lower age threshold.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Minimum pension</strong>: there may be minimum benefit
                  rules and income tests.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                If you have worked in other EU/EEA countries or in countries
                with a <strong>social security agreement</strong> with Italy,
                those periods can often be <strong>totalized</strong> to meet
                the minimum years requirement. Each country then pays its own
                share of the pension.
              </p>

              <h2>Using the Italian Pension Calculator effectively</h2>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong>Estimate your average salary</strong> in today’s
                  euros, not just your current salary.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Use realistic contribution years</strong>, excluding
                  long gaps without contributions.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Try different retirement ages</strong> (e.g. 63, 67,
                  70) to see the impact on your benefit.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Adjust the revaluation rate</strong> to test more
                  conservative or optimistic scenarios.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h3>Limitations of this tool</h3>
              <p>
                The Italian pension system is complex and has changed many times
                (retributivo, misto, contributivo). This calculator:
              </p>
              <ul>
